@Andrzej 
For a long time I never understood the lavish praise of Picasso's work. It seemed like the emperor's new clothes to me: nothing there.  Then, one day years ago, while I was sitting on a bench in the Tate Museum waiting for my husband, I started gazing at a Picasso painting, letting the painting in, and after a while It started to happen.  I don't understand how the door opens and you're with the artist, seeing what they are seeing, feeling what they are trying to express, but it changed my perception of Picasso, and I understood why he was a great painter.

I had read Françoise Gilot's book, "Life With Picasso," and even though she never questioned his greatness, it was clear that he was despicable in his behavior to women. But weirdly, however misogynistic he was in his treatment of them, that painting made me understand that he loved women, adored them.

